Issue 1556: Non-deterministic typecheck-part2 CI failures on Ubuntu 24.04

These two files illustrate the compilation-order dependency that causes
non-deterministic failures when type-checking the Checker Framework itself
with -AuseConservativeDefaultsForUncheckedCode=source.

The actual failure occurs in SubtypeIsSubsetQualifierHierarchy.java:43 (and
SubtypeIsSupersetQualifierHierarchy.java:43) when passing an argument of
type GenericAnnotatedTypeFactory<?,?,?,?> to super(). Both the sub-class
(SubtypeIsSubsetQualifierHierarchy) and the base class
(MostlyNoElementQualifierHierarchy) declare the same parameter type
GenericAnnotatedTypeFactory<?,?,?,?>, but the wildcard bounds may be
annotated differently depending on the compilation order, producing:
  [nullness:argument.type.incompatible]
  [keyfor:argument.type.incompatible]

GenericFactory.java      -- Represents GenericAnnotatedTypeFactory.
                            No @AnnotatedFor("nullness").
WildcardPassthrough.java -- Represents SubtypeIsSubsetQualifierHierarchy
                            (class WildcardPassthrough) and
                            MostlyNoElementQualifierHierarchy
                            (class WildcardBase).
                            Both have @AnnotatedFor("nullness").

Test both compilation orders:

javac -processor org.checkerframework.checker.nullness.NullnessChecker \
  -AuseConservativeDefaultsForUncheckedCode=source \
  GenericFactory.java WildcardPassthrough.java

javac -processor org.checkerframework.checker.nullness.NullnessChecker \
  -AuseConservativeDefaultsForUncheckedCode=source \
  WildcardPassthrough.java GenericFactory.java

If the problem is present, one of these orderings produces errors.
If the fix is working, both orderings produce no errors.
